Read/Load an image¶

There are several ways to read an image from disk, ie. libraries to do that. For instance, the main one are:

opencv¶

import cv2
from skimage.data import chelsea
from matplotlib.pyplot import imshow, axis
%matplotlib inline

im = chelsea()

im_path = "/tmp/chelsea.jpg"

cv2.imwrite(im_path, im)

loaded_im = cv2.imread(im_path)

imshow(loaded_im)
axis("off")

(-0.5, 450.5, 299.5, -0.5)

skimage¶

from skimage.data import chelsea
from skimage.io import imread, imsave
from matplotlib.pyplot import imshow, axis, subplot
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
%matplotlib inline

im = chelsea()

im_path = "/tmp/chelsea.jpg"

imsave(im_path, im)

loaded_im = imread(im_path)

imshow(loaded_im)
axis("off")

(-0.5, 450.5, 299.5, -0.5)

numpy¶

from skimage.data import chelsea
import numpy as np
from matplotlib.pyplot import imshow, axis, subplot
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
%matplotlib inline

im = chelsea()

im_path = "/tmp/chelsea.npy"

np.save(im_path, im)

loaded_im = np.load(im_path)

imshow(loaded_im)
axis("off")

(-0.5, 450.5, 299.5, -0.5)

Image processing ops¶

rescale_intensity¶

There are some operations usual in image intensity. Rescaling an intensity from one range to another is a classical one. Mostly used, for converting any image to 8bit image.

from skimage.exposure import rescale_intensity
from skimage.data import chelsea
from matplotlib.pyplot import imshow, subplot
import numpy as np
im = chelsea()
subplot(1,2,1)
imshow(rescale_intensity(loaded_im, in_range="image", out_range=np.uint8))
axis("off")
subplot(1,2,2)
imshow(rescale_intensity(loaded_im, in_range=(0,128), out_range=np.uint8))
axis("off")

(-0.5, 450.5, 299.5, -0.5)

resize¶

I is often convenient to change the image size via interpolating pixel values. This operation is called resizing and can be done with the standard ibraries too.

opencv¶

import cv2
from cv2 import resize


subplot(1,2,1)
imshow(loaded_im)
axis("off")
subplot(1,2,2)
imshow(resize(im, (64,64), interpolation=cv2.INTER_CUBIC))
axis("off")

(-0.5, 63.5, 63.5, -0.5)
